Awkward Zombie Mario + Rabbids Kingdom Battle

images.description:
Warren Peace

I really loved playing Mario + Rabbids, but everything I enjoyed about the game was in spite of the presence of the Rabbids and everything they stand for.

I noticed the game refuses to let you make a squad without any Rabbids on it. I'm sure everyone else who played the game noticed too, because it is the human body's natural response to try to do so when given the opportunity.

Hop to it 

Mario is only holding back his true power to give the Rabbids a fighting chance at survival.

Pipe down 

He's probably happier that way.

data.title: Guarantee of Freshness Part II
data.description:
Posted this: https://imgur.com/gallery/NJAaQPs and a bunch of folks worried that it was a live fish being tortured. Seriously, y'all need to get out more. Nobody trying to prepare food cuts up a live animal. Sushi-grade fish are killed by running a wire into their brain and down their spinal column. The movement is just spasm, and as you can see, it doesn't need a head or guts or a central nervous system to work. 

It's delightfully creepy though.

images.description:
Juicy

The original female vampire costume in Bravely Default was actually considered TOO SEXY for American eyeballs, so the localized version of the game threw some more layers on there! I guess it's still supposed to be way hot, but I thought it was funny that it was also the class that mimics gross monster attacks like barf jets.

Fashion Deux Pas

I like that Bravely Default (and other job-system games) pair gaining someone's powers with also gaining their wardrobe.

Duress Code

Bravely Default is a game that tries to have sad, poignant moments, but then forgets that it let you dress your entire party in discount Elvis halloween costumes and wear them to the funeral.

Saki from Zombie Land Saga, who was a teenager in the 90s, mimics Rumiko Takahashi's "shocked hands"

images.description:
For those of you who might not be aware, Rumiko Takahashi is one of the most celebrated mangaka and creator of series like Urusei Yatsura, Ranma 1/2, and Inuyasha.

Saki seems to have been alive some time in the 90s, when Takahashi was at the height of her popularity. Based off what we know of her personality and past, it's most likely she was a huge Takahashi fan.
